    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1978-06-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1978-06-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="282"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d282">
                <head>282. Letter From President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> to
                    Governor General of the Solomon Islands <persName corresp="#p_DB_1"
                        >Devesi</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d282fn1">Source: Carter Library, Plains File,
                        President’s Personal Foreign Affairs File, Box 3, Solomon Islands, 6–10/78.
                        No classification marking. The Solomon Islands gained independence on July
                        7.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1978-06-27">June 27, 1978</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Governor General:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>The American people join me in sending best wishes to you and the people of the
                    Solomon Islands. I am pleased to inform you that, as the Solomon Islands attains
                    independence, the United States Government extends its recognition. It is our
                    hope that, with your agreement, diplomatic relations can be established quickly
                    between our two countries.</p>
                <p>We believe that friendly and productive relations will develop between the United
                    States and the independent Solomon Islands. Significant ties between our two
                    countries began during World War II when many Americans served in the Pacific
                    area and cooperated closely with Solomon Islanders. These ties have continued,
                    nurtured by our mutual concern for economic progress, human rights, and
                    democratic government.</p>
                <p>We are confident that the friendship between our two countries will grow even
                    closer in the years to come. The Government and people of the United States
                    share your aspirations for the progress and welfare of the people of the Solomon
                    Islands, and we look forward to working <pb facs="0961" n="932" xml:id="pg_932"
                    /> together with you in your efforts to realize those goals and to contribute to
                    peace and prosperity for all mankind.</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Jimmy Carter</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
